{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17612870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17612870"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:28:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:28:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16294"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16294","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16294"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8985"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116071"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8985","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8985"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16294"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98067"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1992"},{"type":"tags","id":"4904"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"7197"},{"type":"tags","id":"7199"},{"type":"tags","id":"7200"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21376"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21379"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116071"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe perception of taste requires multiple cranial nerves working together to transmit sensory information from different regions of the tongue and oropharynx to the brain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the cranial nerves responsible for taste sensation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Vagus nerve, facial nerve, and glossopharyngeal nerve","Trigeminal nerve, facial nerve, and hypoglossal nerve","Facial nerve and glossopharyngeal nerve only","Vagus nerve and glossopharyngeal nerve only","Trigeminal nerve and facial nerve only"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETaste sensation is transmitted by three cranial nerves: the \u003Cstrong\u003Efacial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E carries taste from the anterior two-thirds of the tongue, the \u003Cstrong\u003Eglossopharyngeal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E carries taste from the posterior third of the tongue, and the \u003Cstrong\u003Evagus nerve\u003C/strong\u003E carries taste from the epiglottis and posterior pharynx.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etrigeminal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E provides general sensation to the tongue but not taste, whilst the \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypoglossal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E provides motor innervation to the tongue muscles. All three nerves (facial, glossopharyngeal, and vagus) are required for taste sensation from the entire tongue and posterior oropharynx. The taste information is then processed in the nucleus of the solitary tract in the brainstem.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Taste sensations from the tongue are transmitted by three cranial nerves: facial nerve (anterior two-thirds), glossopharyngeal nerve (posterior third), and vagus nerve (epiglottis and posterior pharynx).","Each taste nerve innervates a specific region of the tongue, with some overlap at boundaries."],"references":["Netter, F. H. (2015). Netter\u0027s Cranial Nerve Collection E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Gravina SA, Yep GL, Khan M. Human biology of taste. Ann Saudi Med. 2013 May-Jun;33(3):217-22. doi: 10.5144/0256-4947.2013.217. PMID: 23793421; PMCID: PMC6078535."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98067"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16294"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98067","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98067"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-27T13:33:38+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-27T13:36:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8985"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116071"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationship